            "description": "Ful\u00fcs, the plural of fals, is originally a Greek-Latin\nform (\u03a6\u039f\u039b\u039b\u0399\u03a3), which might derive indirectly\nfrom Aramaic or Hebrew1. The word reached the\nArab world through the Byzantines and was \u2018Arabicised\u2019\nfrom the word follis, which most likely\nmeant the struck coinage made of red copper,\nalthough it was also used for struck coinage made\nof bronze.\nAfter the Islamic conquest, the Arabs used\nthese ful\u00fcs in business, retaining the original foreign\ndesignation. ",
